3958d-1 | 2026-06-13T21:54:28Z | session:3958dfae-7703-499c-b93a-b4def20d006e | Assistant: My diagnosis was wrong — the fill path wasn't the issue. The line itself looks stepped because the underlying weight data has many repeated values (same weight for multiple days), and monotone interpolation connects them with literal flat segments. The fix is to plot a smoothed (EWMA) line while keeping the raw dots. \n  \n Assistant: Now update `areaFillPath` to use `smoothedLine` too: \n  \n Assistant: Now the same changes for `LandscapeFocusChart`: \n  \n Assistant: Now I need to update the `visible` variable in `LandscapeFocusChart.areaFillPath` to use `smoothedLine` instead of `inCutReadings`: \n  \n Assistant: Now build and deploy: \n  \n Assistant: Building now. The actual cause: weight data had many consecutive days at the same value (whole-pound readings), so monotone interpolation drew literal flat segments → staircase. The fix plots a 25%-alpha EWMA trend line (smooth) while keeping the individual dots as raw readings, same pattern WeightChart already uses for its moving average. \n 
3958d-2 | 2026-06-13T21:54:30Z | session:3958dfae-7703-499c-b93a-b4def20d006e | The fix: use Catmull-Rom cubic bezier curves in `areaFillPath` to match the smooth line. \n  \n Assistant: The root cause: the gradient fill area under the line was drawn with straight `addLine` calls between each daily reading, creating sharp right-angle steps. The `LineMark` itself uses `.monotone` interpolation (smooth), but the fill path didn't — and since both are the same dark color, the stepped fill made the whole line look blocky. \n  \n Fixed in both `ActiveCutMinichart.swift` and `LandscapeFocusChart.swift` by replacing the straight-line fill path with Catmull-Rom cubic bezier curves, which closely approximates the monotone spline the chart line uses.
