18aed-2 | 2026-06-17T08:22:28Z | session:18aedfc3-5869-408c-a87a-9618ad497cfa | Quick math check: if **weight** is your position, then: \n - **1st derivative** = rate at which weight is changing (e.g. lbs/week) — *this is what you described: "the speed at which my weight is changing."* \n - **2nd derivative** = how that rate itself is speeding up or slowing down (is your loss accelerating or stalling). \n  \n So what you asked for in words — "the rate of speed at which my weight is changing" — is the **first derivative**. The second derivative would tell you whether your cut is accelerating or plateauing. Let me look at the current chart so I can recommend concretely. [...] ## On your "second derivative?" question \n  \n Your words — *"the rate of speed at which my weight is changing"* — are the **first derivative** (velocity: lb/wk), and that's what I built. The **second derivative** would be acceleration — whether your loss is speeding up or stalling. I went with the first because it matches what you described; if you actually want the "am I plateauing?" acceleration view, that's a quick follow-up (could even be a third page). [...] User: I want to be able to slide on the daily chart in the main screen and see a chart, same UI (except the min/max/avg trend lines) of the second derivative (is this correct?) -- what I want to see is the rate of speed at which my weight is changing during the cut [...] 2. **Page 2 — Rate of change**: swipe left to see the **first derivative** of your weight line — how fast your weight is moving right now. Same visual UI (smooth line + dots + gradient fill), **minus** the best/worst/avg trend lines and target rule, as you asked. It adds: [...]    - a dashed **zero baseline** so you can see when you cross from losing to gaining, \n    - a **current-rate readout** in the corner showing **both** units, e.g. `−1.2 lb/wk` and `−0.17 lb/day`. [...]    - a dashed **zero baseline** so you can see when you cross from losing to gaining, \n    -