18aed-23 | 2026-06-17T09:01:29Z | session:18aedfc3-5869-408c-a87a-9618ad497cfa | **The "+1.9 lb/wk" is real but misleading.** The old code measured the rate over just a ±1-day window. The first derivative of *daily* weigh-ins is dominated by water-weight noise: a single day's water retention is ±1–2 lb, which is a ±7–14 lb/**wk** swing — that completely swamps the ~0.1 lb/day your cut actually moves. So the "current" number was really just measuring "did today's water tick up vs. 2 days ago," and it landed positive by chance. The underlying trend is down; the window was far too short to see it. \n  \n The fix: measure the rate as the slope of a **~2-week regression**, which cleanly recovers the real direction (negative while cutting) instead of daily noise. Let me replace my ±3-day version with that: [...] **The sign bug — root cause.** The "+1.9 lb/wk gaining" wasn't a flipped sign; it was a **too-short measurement window**. The old code computed the rate over ±1 day. The first derivative of *daily* weigh-ins is mostly water noise — a single day's water swing (±1–2 lb) is ±7–14 lb/**wk** of apparent "rate," which buries the ~0.1 lb/day your cut actually moves and flips the sign around at random. It happened to land positive. \n  \n Now the rate is the **slope of a ~2-week least-squares regression** (±7-day window, date-based so logging gaps don't distort it). Over two weeks the water noise averages out and the real downward trend shows through — so while you're cutting, the number and the line should sit **below zero (losing)**. The "current" headline is now the trailing ~1–2 week trend, not "did today's water tick up." [...] This doesn't bias the *rate* (the dupes are identical, so the slope is unaffected — which is why the headline is still correct). But it **wrecks the smoothing**: the 5-day average is indexed by *reading*, not *day*, so with ~2 readings/day it actually only spans ~2.5 real days → the line is far noisier than it should be. Combine that with genuine water swings (Jun 15 jumped +2.4 lb then −2.8 lb the next day) and you get the jagged shape. \n  [...] 1. **Dedupe to one point per calendar day** before computing the rate — smoother, honest line. \n 2. **Overlay the weight trend** on the rate chart (as you asked). [...] - **Day-deduped rate** — collapses the duplicate readings to one point per day before computing, so the smoothing window is a true ~2 weeks instead of ~2.5 days. The line should be noticeably calmer. [...] also, the chart is very blocky -- there's no smoothness on the line [...] Fixes: scale to fit the data and just *include* zero (no wasted half, nothing clipped), regress over the already-smoothed weight line, add a light smoothing pass, and use Catmull-Rom interpolation for a smooth curve. [...] Assistant: Now switch the rate line to Catmull-Rom for a smooth curve: \n  \n Assistant: Removed the per-point dots too (they emphasized the discreteness). Building and deploying: [...] - **Smooth line** — three changes stack here: regress over the *smoothed* weight line (kills the quantization stair-steps at the source), add a light ±2 moving-average pass over the rate series, and render with **Catmull-Rom** interpolation. Also dropped the per-point dots so it reads as one fluid curve. \n  [...] 2. **Wasted top half.** I made the y-domain *symmetric* around zero, but a cut is essentially always negative — so the entire "gaining" half above zero is empty white space, and your actual data is crammed into the bottom half. \n 3. **The fill leaks below the chart.** See that thin spike punching down through the bottom edge into the tab bar near the center? Your deepest-loss day exceeds the (percentile-clamped) scale, so its point lands *outside* the plot and the fill bleeds out. [...] Assistant: Now the y-domain — fit the data and include zero (no wasted half, nothing clipped): [...] - **No more wasted half** — the y-domain now fits your actual data and just *includes* zero (instead of forcing a symmetric 